# Code Quality Rules

## Folder Structure
- Group everything related to one page/feature inside one main folder
- Inside that folder, create subfolders: `components/`, `hooks/`, `helpers/`, `constants/`, `types/`
- Example: `features/UserProfile/components/`, `features/UserProfile/hooks/`
- Break large files into smaller focused pieces and import them

## Naming
- No abbreviations in variable, function, or file names
- Use full descriptive names: `userProfileData` not `usrPrfDt`, `isLoading` not `isLd`
- Event handler functions must start with `handle`: `handleSubmit`, `handleUserDelete`, `handleInputChange`
- Boolean variables must start with `is`, `has`, `can`, `should`: `isModalOpen`, `hasPermission`

## No Magic Strings or Numbers
- Never use raw strings or numbers directly in logic or JSX
- Create enums or constants files for all repeated or meaningful values

```ts
// ❌ Bad
if (status === 'active') ...
if (role === 'admin') ...

// ✅ Good
enum UserStatus { Active = 'active', Inactive = 'inactive' }
enum UserRole { Admin = 'admin', Viewer = 'viewer' }
if (status === UserStatus.Active) ...
```

## DRY — Don't Repeat Yourself
- If the same logic appears more than once, extract it into a helper function or custom hook
- If the same JSX pattern repeats, extract it into a component
- Shared helpers go in `helpers/`, shared hooks go in `hooks/`

## KISS — Keep It Simple
- Only apply abstractions when they genuinely make the code simpler and easier to read
- Do not over-engineer. If a simple function is clear enough, don't wrap it
- Write code for other engineers first — clarity beats cleverness

## React Performance
- Use `useMemo` for expensive computed values that depend on specific deps
- Use `useCallback` for functions passed as props or used in dependency arrays
- Only add these when there is a clear reason — do not wrap everything by default

```ts
// Use when the calculation is heavy or passed as a dependency
const sortedUsers = useMemo(() => sortUsers(users), [users])
const handleDelete = useCallback((id: string) => deleteUser(id), [deleteUser])
```

## Functions
- Each function does one thing only
- Keep functions short — if it needs scrolling, consider splitting it
- Use `handle` prefix for all event-driven functions
- Extract complex conditions into named boolean variables or helper functions

```ts
// ❌ Bad
if (user.age > 18 && user.isVerified && !user.isBanned) ...

// ✅ Good
const canAccessContent = user.age > 18 && user.isVerified && !user.isBanned
if (canAccessContent) ...
```

## Components
- One component per file
- Props interface defined above the component, named `[ComponentName]Props`
- Keep JSX clean — move logic out of JSX into variables or handler functions before the return

## General
- Always ask: "Would a new engineer understand this in 30 seconds?"
- Apply all rules where they make sense — not blindly, but with judgment
- Readable and maintainable code is always the goal
